# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: altium-designer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:altium-designer/altium-designer] Altium Designer has roots in 1985, launched by Altium Limited (named Protel Systems Pty Ltd. at that time) as a PCB design tool for MS-DOS named Protel PCB (which later became Autotrax and Easytrax).
[src:altium-designer/altium-designer] Altium Designer was officially launched by Altium in 2005.
[src:altium-designer/altium-designer] Originally it was sold only in Australia, with Protel PCB marketed internationally by HST Technology since 1986.
[src:altium-designer/altium-designer] The product became available in the United States, Canada, and Mexico beginning in 1986, marketed by San Diego–based ACCEL Technologies, Inc., under the name Tango PCB.
[src:altium-designer/altium-designer] In 1987, Protel launched the circuit diagram editor *Protel Schematic* for DOS.
[src:altium-designer/altium-designer] In 1998, *Protel 98* consolidated all components, including *Advanced Schematic* and *Advanced PCB*, into one environment.
[src:altium-designer/altium-designer] *Protel 99* in 1999 introduced the first integrated 3D visualization of the PCB assembly.
[src:altium-designer/altium-designer] It was followed by *Protel 99 SE* in 2000.
[src:altium-designer/altium-designer] Altium Designer version 6.8 from 2007 was the first to offer 3D visualization and clearance checking of PCBs directly within the PCB editor.
[src:altium-designer/altium-designer] In 2001, the company adopted the name Altium Limited.
[src:altium-designer/altium-designer] In 2008, Altium Designer added direct integration with STEP mechanical CAD file formats, enabling dynamic linking between the PCB design environment and external MCAD software.
[src:altium-designer/altium-designer] Version 10, released in 2011, introduced product data management capabilities.
[src:altium-designer/altium-designer] Altium Designer 2013 opened the platform to third-party partners and system integrators.
[src:altium-designer/altium-designer] Altium Designer 18, released in 2018, introduced a 64-bit architecture, multiboard design functionality, and a redesigned bill-of-materials management system.
[src:altium-designer/altium-designer] Altium Designer 19, released in 2018, added connectivity with Altium 365, the company's cloud-based platform for multi-domain collaboration and real-time information sharing.
[src:altium-designer/altium-designer] In 2021, Altium rejected a takeover bid from software company Autodesk, which had previously acquired the EDA tool EAGLE in 2016, valuing Altium at approximately A$5.05 billion.
[src:altium-designer/altium-designer] In February 2024, Renesas Electronics agreed to acquire Altium for approximately US$5.9 billion.
[src:altium-designer/altium-designer] The acquisition was completed in August 2024, making Altium a wholly owned subsidiary of Renesas.
[src:altium-designer/altium-designer] Beginning in 2025, Altium introduced three subscription-based platform solutions built on its existing technology: Altium Discover, Altium Develop, and Altium Agile.
[src:altium-designer/altium-designer] Altium Designer and Altium 365 continue to serve as the underlying design and cloud platform, with each solution bundling varying levels of access to those tools and capabilities into tiered subscription offerings.
[src:altium-designer/altium-designer] Altium Designer is no longer offered as a standalone product and is instead available as part of the Altium Develop and Altium Agile platform solutions.
[src:altium-designer/altium-designer] It integrates with several component distributors (via the Octopart platform) for access to manufacturer's data, inventory information, lifecycle status, and additional technical information, which is not available in component datasheets.
[src:altium-designer/altium-designer] It also has interactive 3D editing of the board, and exporting of a design into MCAD file formats (such as STEP).
[src:altium-designer/altium-designer] Users can create multiple types of designs, including multi-layer rigid PCBs with high layer counts, rigid-flex PCBs, flexible printed circuits, and more specialized designs like metal-backed or ceramic PCBs.
[src:altium-designer/altium-designer] Altium Develop represents the professional design and collaboration tier of the Altium platform.
[src:altium-designer/altium-designer] It brings together Altium Designer and Altium 365 into a unified framework for advanced electronic product development, enabling multidisciplinary teams to co-create, manage components, and prepare designs for manufacturing.
[src:altium-designer/altium-designer] Develop is aimed at professional engineering teams building production-ready hardware who require robust design environments, structured collaboration, and system-level integrations that connect electrical, mechanical, and manufacturing domains.
[src:altium-designer/altium-designer] Altium Agile delivers enterprise-grade process management and workflow orchestration for organizations building complex hardware systems.
[src:altium-designer/altium-designer] It extends the Altium platform to enable controlled, multi-team collaboration and end-to-end visibility across engineering operations.
[src:altium-designer/altium-designer] Altium Designer supports import & export of various PCB and CAD data exchange file formats.
[src:altium-designer/altium-designer] The tool's native file formats are the binary file formats `*.SchDoc` and `*.PcbDoc`.
[src:altium-designer/altium-designer] It can also import and export AutoCAD `*.dwg`/`*.dxf` and ISO 10303-21 STEP file formats.
[src:altium-designer/altium] The history of Altium dates to 1985 with the founding of Protel Systems Pty Ltd by electronics designer Nicholas Martin.
[src:altium-designer/altium] He was working at the University of Tasmania in the 1980s.
[src:altium-designer/altium] He saw an opportunity to make the design of electronics product affordable, by marrying the techniques of electronics design to the PC platform.
[src:altium-designer/altium] The company launched its first product in 1985, a DOS-based printed circuit board (PCB) layout and design tool.
[src:altium-designer/altium] Protel PCB was marketed internationally by HST Technology Pty Ltd. since 1986.
[src:altium-designer/altium] In October 1986 the San Diego–based ACCEL Technologies, Inc. acquired marketing and support responsibilities of the PCB program for the US, Canada and Mexico under the name Tango PCB.
[src:altium-designer/altium] In 1987, Protel launched the circuit diagram editor Protel Schematic for DOS.
[src:altium-designer/altium] This was followed by Autotrax and Easytrax in 1988.
[src:altium-designer/altium] In the 1990s, the company began developing a unified electronics design system, which uses a single data model to hold all of the design data required to create a product.
[src:altium-designer/altium] FPGA, PCB and embedded software development processes were unified with a common project view and data model.
[src:altium-designer/altium] A variety of editing tools could then be used to access and manipulate the design, covering areas such as board layout and design, schematic capture, routing (EDA), testing, analysis and FPGA design.
[src:altium-designer/altium] In 1991, Protel released Advanced Schematic/PCB 1.0 for Windows, the world's first Windows-based PCB design system.
[src:altium-designer/altium] It also began acquisition of various companies with the technologies needed to create a unified electronics design solution, including Accolade Design Automation in 1998.
[src:altium-designer/altium] In August 1999, Altium went public on the Australian Securities Exchange.
[src:altium-designer/altium] The company continued to develop and release new versions of this design tool, including Protel 98 in 1998, Protel 99 in 1999 and Protel 99 SE in 2000.
[src:altium-designer/altium] In 2000, Altium acquired ACCEL with whom they previously partnered with in 1986.
[src:altium-designer/altium] In 2001, the company changed its name from Protel Systems to Altium and continued to expand throughout the United States, Europe, and Asia.
[src:altium-designer/altium] It also made more acquisitions including embedded software developer Tasking in 2001 for A$73.4 million and EDA software distributor Hoschar AG in 2002.
[src:altium-designer/altium] Protel DXP was issued in 2003, Protel 2004 in 2004, Altium Designer 6.0 in 2005.
[src:altium-designer/altium] In 2010, Altium acquired Morfik Technology Pty Ltd., a developer of visual design tools for engineering and deploying cloud-based software applications.
[src:altium-designer/altium] Morfik's founders originally worked for Altium/Protel before leaving to found the company after Altium's IPO.
[src:altium-designer/altium] In 2011, Altium announced it would be expanding its presence in Shanghai, China, in the second half of 2011 to take advantage of lower wages.
[src:altium-designer/altium] On October 15, 2012, the Altium board removed Nick Martin as CEO and named executive vice chairman Kayvan Oboudiyat to replace him.
[src:altium-designer/altium] On January 16, 2014, Altium announced Kayvan Oboudiyat's retirement and succession by Aram Mirkazemi as CEO.
[src:altium-designer/altium] In May of the same year, Altium announced that the core R&D operations for its flagship PCB CAD tools would again relocate in a "cost neutral" move to San Diego, California.
[src:altium-designer/altium] In 2015, Altium acquired Octopart, a search engine for electronic and industrial parts.
[src:altium-designer/altium] The same year, it acquired the cloud-based electronic component management system company Ciiva.
[src:altium-designer/altium] Additional acquisitions by the company have included enterprise PLM integration solutions provider Perception Software in 2016 and cloud-based EDA tool company Upverter in 2017.
[src:altium-designer/altium] In 2018, Altium acquired Brooklyn-based PCB:NG, an online service for turnkey PCB assembly that introduced instantaneous Design for Manufacturability (DFM) checks for orders varying in volume and complexity.
[src:altium-designer/altium] On 7 June 2021, it was revealed that Altium rejected a bid from Autodesk, who had already bought the EDA tool EAGLE in 2016, valuing the company at A$5.05 billion.
[src:altium-designer/altium] In December 2023, Altium acquired Valispace, a systems and requirements engineering software platform based in Germany, for approximately $15.6 million.
[src:altium-designer/altium] The acquisition was intended to integrate systems and requirements engineering capabilities with Altium's cloud platform, Altium 365.
[src:altium-designer/altium] In February 2024, Renesas Electronics agreed to acquire Altium for US$5.9 billion.
[src:altium-designer/altium] The acquisition was completed in August 2024, with Altium becoming a subsidiary of Renesas Electronics.
[src:altium-designer/altium] In January 2025, Altium acquired Part Analytics, a Milwaukee-based provider of an AI-powered supply chain management platform for the electronics industry.
[src:altium-designer/altium] The acquisition was intended to integrate enterprise-level component planning and procurement capabilities into Altium 365.
[src:altium-designer/altium] In March 2025, Renesas and Altium announced Renesas 365, Powered by Altium, a joint platform designed to streamline electronics system development from silicon selection through system lifecycle management, built on the Altium 365 cloud platform.
[src:altium-designer/altium] The platform was expected to be generally available in early 2026.
[src:altium-designer/altium] Altium develops software and platforms for the design and realisation of electronic products, including printed circuit boards (PCBs).
[src:altium-designer/altium] Its tools support every stage of electronics development, from schematic capture and PCB layout to sourcing, version-control and manufacturing hand-off—and are used across industries such as automotive, aerospace, defence, and telecommunications.
[src:altium-designer/altium] Altium Designer and Altium 365 serve as the underlying design and cloud platform across all of Altium's solutions.
[src:altium-designer/altium] Beginning in 2024–2025, Altium reorganised its commercial offerings under three subscription-based platform tiers — Altium Discover, Altium Develop, and Altium Agile, each bundling varying levels of access to those underlying tools and capabilities.
[src:altium-designer/altium] Ocotpart Discover is a platform that equips engineers with a solution-oriented approach to finding, exploring, and selecting components and technologies that meet specific design requirements.
[src:altium-designer/altium] It captures the context around design intent to enable more solution-focused engagement, strengthens communication and collaboration with manufacturers and distributors, and provides actionable insight and intelligence to support faster, more informed decision-making.
[src:altium-designer/altium] Altium Develop is a collaborative platform for multidisciplinary electronics product development centered around PCB design, sourcing, and manufacturing.
[src:altium-designer/altium] The product features and price point are suitable for individual contractors or freelance designers, hobbyists, and professional engineers working at large companies.
[src:altium-designer/altium] For engineers working on larger teams, collaboration and data management features through a cloud platform provide real-time insight across the entire lifecycle of a project.
[src:altium-designer/altium] Every change, comment, and decision is captured in context, giving collaborators shared visibility without the need for formal status checks.
[src:altium-designer/altium] Users can collaborate across electrical, mechanical, sourcing, and manufacturing disciplines within a unified environment.
[src:altium-designer/altium] Users can access their product data, functional requirements, and version histories within this environment.
[src:altium-designer/altium] Engineers, 3rd party stakeholders, and other team members can be given access to a project at any stage in the product development process.
[src:altium-designer/altium] Altium Develop integrates industry-leading PCB design through Altium Designer, expands project visibility to all functional experts, and displays system requirements contextually within supported design file formats.
[src:altium-designer/altium] The platform can also display supply chain data for components directly in libraries, schematics, and PCB layouts, which includes pricing, availability, and lifecycle insights to guide sourcing decisions.
[src:altium-designer/altium] Users can also invite manufacturers to review a project by giving direct access to the design data before a design is sent for manufacturer, allowing potential product defects to be identified early.
[src:altium-designer/altium] Altium Agile is a platform-based solution for electronics product and systems development that connects users and engineering environments through integrations with tools such as Jira, enterprise PLM systems, SiliconExpert, and Z2Data.
[src:altium-designer/altium] The solution establishes structure, governance, and managed processes across people, tools, data, and workflows while preserving the speed and creative agility needed in electronics engineering.
[src:altium-designer/altium] Altium Agile is delivered through two editions: Agile Teams and Agile Enterprise.
[src:altium-designer/altium] Each edition is aligned to a distinct organisational profile and set of requirements.
[src:altium-designer/altium] These editions correspond to the broader executive vision that separates companies with growth and organisational needs from those with regulatory and digitalisation needs.
[src:altium-designer/altium] Agile Teams is designed for smaller companies, workgroups, or organisations that face increasing complexity in electronics development but do not operate under extensive regulatory or digital-transformation mandates.
[src:altium-designer/altium] It provides an out-of-the-box environment with minimal setup and no need for significant IT infrastructure.
[src:altium-designer/altium] Teams focuses on foundational structure and control, enabling organisations to solve challenges such as unmanaged data, disconnected tools, ad-hoc processes, and supply-chain risk.
[src:altium-designer/altium] Agile Enterprise is tailored for larger, digitally mature, and often heavily regulated companies that require deeper integrations, stringent compliance, and enterprise-level governance.
[src:altium-designer/altium] It extends electronics development into the broader product development ecosystem, connecting ECAD data and workflows with PLM, ERP, requirements management, compliance systems, and other enterprise platforms.
[src:altium-designer/altium] Enterprise emphasises traceability, data security, managed processes, and integration throughout the digital enterprise.
[src:altium-designer/altium] Octopart is a searchable electronic-parts intelligence engine offering up-to-date availability, pricing, CAD models and parametric data for millions of components, and is operated by Altium.
[src:altium-designer/altium] Octopart includes BOM Tool, which is a browser-based application for managing Bills of Materials (BOMs).
[src:altium-designer/altium] It allows users to upload or create BOMs and automatically match components to Octopart's database of electronic parts.
[src:altium-designer/altium] The tool provides insights into part availability across distributors, current pricing, lifecycle status, compliance information, and alternative and cross-referenced parts.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] This page is a comparison of electronic design automation (EDA) software which is used today to design the near totality of electronic devices.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] Modern electronic devices are too complex to be designed without the help of a computer.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] Electronic devices may consist of integrated circuits (ICs), integrated circuit substrates, printed circuit boards (PCBs), field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs) or a combination of them.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] Integrated circuits may consist of a combination of digital and analog circuits.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] These circuits can contain a combination of transistors, resistors, capacitors or specialized components such as analog neural networks, antennas or fuses.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] The design of each of these electronic devices generally proceeds from a high- to a low-level of abstraction.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] For FPGAs the low-level description consists of a binary file to be flashed into the gate array, while for an integrated circuit or printed circuit board the low-level description consists of a layout file which describes the masks to be used for lithography inside a foundry.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] Each design step requires specialized tools, and many of these tools can be used for designing multiple types of electronic circuits.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] For example, a program for high-level digital synthesis can usually be used both for IC digital design as well as for programming an FPGA.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] Similarly, a tool for schematic-capture and analog simulation can generally be used both for analog IC design and for PCB design.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] In the case of integrated circuits (ICs) for example, a single chip may contain today more than 20 billion transistors and, as a general rule, every single transistor in a chip must work as intended.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] Since a single VLSI mask set can cost up to 10-100 millions, trial and error approaches are not economically viable.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] To minimize the risk of any design mistakes, the design flow is heavily automated.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] EDA software assists the designer in every step of the design process and every design step is accompanied by heavy test phases.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] Errors may be present in the high-level code already, such as for the Pentium FDIV floating-point unit bug, or it can be inserted all the way down to physical synthesis, such as a missing wire, or a timing violation.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] These vendors offer software bundles which allow to cover the full spectrum of IC design, from HDL synthesis to physical synthesis and verification.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] The development of EDA software for IC design is tightly connected with the development of technology nodes.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] The properties of a specific semiconductor foundry, such as the transistor models, the physical characteristics and the design rules, are usually encoded in file formats which are proprietary to one or more EDA vendors.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] This set of files constitutes the process design kit (PDK) and it is usually developed as a joint effort between the foundry and an EDA vendor.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] Foundries therefore usually release PDKs which are compatible only for one specific EDA bundle.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] The information contained inside PDKs is usually considered confidential.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] PDKs are therefore usually protected by non disclosure agreements (NDAs) and may be shipped in an incomplete or in an encrypted form to the designers.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] Of these, LTSpice, TINA-TI, Micro-cap are free proprietary applications based on SPICE.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] Micro-Cap was released as freeware in July 2019, when its parent company Spectrum Software closed down while LTSpice has been free for a long time.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] PDF, PNG, SVG, JSON, Gerber, Excellon, Pick and Place CSV file, CSV-formatted drill chart, Bill of Materials CSV file, Altium netlist, FreePCB netlist, PADS Layout Netlist, Spice netlist.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] EAGLE/KiCad libraries, Altium/Allegro Schematics, DXF, SVG, STEP, etc.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] Gerber, IPC-2581C, ODB++, EDIF netlists, D356 netlists, JEP30, Pick and Place CSV file, CSV-formatted drill chart, Bill of Materials CSV file.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] PDF, Gerber, GerberX2, Excellon, ODB++, DXF, IDF, PKP, testpoint file, metafile, BMP.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] Free and open-source (FOSS) EDA software bundles are currently under fast development mainly thanks to the DARPA and Google's openROAD project.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] The OpenROAD project offers a complete stack of tools from high-level synthesis down to layout generation The flow includes Yosys for logic synthesis, OpenLane for physical synthesis and targets the SkyWater 130 nm PDK.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] The flow is currently utilized to submit design for free fabrication at Google.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] High-level synthesis software can generally be used for the design of both application-specific integrated circuits (ASICs) and field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs).
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] Most high-level synthesis software is used to edit and verify code written in one of the mainstream hardware description languages (HDL) like VHDL or Verilog.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] Other tools instead operate at a higher level of abstraction and allow to synthesize HDL code starting from languages like Chisel or SpinalHDL.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] The higher abstraction of such languages enables formal verification of HDL code.
[src:altium-designer/comparison-of-eda-software] This list does not include schematic editors or simulators since these can generally be used both for Integrated Circuits (ICs) and for Printed Circuit Board (PCB) as long as device models are available.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] PCBs are used to connect or "wire" components to one another in an electronic circuit.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Electrical components may be fixed to conductive pads on the outer layers, generally by soldering, which both electrically connects and mechanically fastens the components to the board.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Another manufacturing process adds vias, metal-lined drilled holes that enable electrical interconnections between conductive layers, to boards with more than a single side.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Printed circuit boards are used in nearly all electronic products today.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Alternatives to PCBs include wire wrap and point-to-point construction, both once popular but now rarely used.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] PCBs require additional design effort to lay out the circuit, but manufacturing and assembly can be automated.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Electronic design automation software is available to do much of the work of layout.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Mass-producing circuits with PCBs is cheaper and faster than with other wiring methods, as components are mounted and wired in one operation.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Large numbers of PCBs can be fabricated at the same time, and the layout has to be done only once.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] PCBs can also be made manually in small quantities, with reduced benefits.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] PCBs can be single-sided (one copper layer), double-sided (two copper layers on both sides of one substrate layer), or multi-layer (stacked layers of substrate with copper plating sandwiched between each and on the outside layers).
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Multi-layer PCBs provide much higher component density, because circuit traces on the inner layers would otherwise take up surface space between components.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] The rise in popularity of multilayer PCBs with more than two, and especially with more than four, copper planes was concurrent with the adoption of surface-mount technology.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] However, multilayer PCBs make repair, analysis, and field modification of circuits much more difficult and usually impractical.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] The world market for bare PCBs exceeded US$60.2 billion in 2014, and was estimated at $80.33 billion in 2024, forecast to be $96.57 billion for 2029, growing at 4.87% per annum.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Before the development of printed circuit boards, electrical and electronic circuits were wired point-to-point on a chassis.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Typically, the chassis was a sheet metal frame or pan, sometimes with a wooden bottom.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Components were attached to the chassis, usually by insulators when the connecting point on the chassis was metal, and then their leads were connected directly or with jumper wires by soldering, or sometimes using crimp connectors, wire connector lugs on screw terminals, or other methods.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Circuits were large, bulky, heavy, and relatively fragile (even discounting the breakable glass envelopes of the vacuum tubes that were often included in the circuits), and production was labor-intensive, so the products were expensive.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Development of the methods used in modern printed circuit boards started early in the 20th century.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] In 1903, a German inventor, Albert Hanson, described flat foil conductors laminated to an insulating board, in multiple layers.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Thomas Edison experimented with chemical methods of plating conductors onto linen paper in 1904.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Arthur Berry in 1913 patented a print-and-etch method in the UK, and in the United States Max Schoop obtained a patent to flame-spray metal onto a board through a patterned mask.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Charles Ducas in 1925 patented a method of electroplating circuit patterns.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Predating the printed circuit invention, and similar in spirit, was John Sargrove's 1936–1947 Electronic Circuit Making Equipment (ECME) that sprayed metal onto a Bakelite plastic board.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] The ECME could produce three radio boards per minute.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] The Austrian engineer Paul Eisler invented the printed circuit as part of a radio set while working in the UK around 1936.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] In 1941 a multi-layer printed circuit was used in German magnetic influence naval mines.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Around 1943 the United States began to use the technology on a large scale to make proximity fuzes for use in World War II.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Such fuzes required an electronic circuit that could withstand being fired from a gun, and could be produced in quantity.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] The Centralab Division of Globe Union submitted a proposal using thick-film technology which met the requirements.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] A ceramic plate would be screenprinted with metallic paint for conductors and carbon material for resistors, with ceramic disc capacitors and subminiature vacuum tubes soldered in place.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] The technique proved viable, and the resulting patent on the process, which was classified by the U.S.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] It was not until 1984 that the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) awarded Harry W.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Rubinstein its Cledo Brunetti Award for early key contributions to the development of printed components and conductors on a common insulating substrate.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Rubinstein was honored in 1984 by his alma mater, the University of Wisconsin-Madison, for his innovations in the technology of printed electronic circuits and the fabrication of capacitors.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] This invention also represents a step in the development of integrated circuit technology, as not only wiring but also passive components were fabricated on the ceramic substrate.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] In 1948, the US released the invention for commercial use.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Printed circuits did not become commonplace in consumer electronics until the mid-1950s, after the *Auto-Sembly* process was developed by the United States Army.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] At around the same time in the UK work along similar lines was carried out by Geoffrey Dummer, then at the RRDE.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Motorola was an early leader in bringing the process into consumer electronics, announcing in August 1952 the adoption of "plated circuits" in home radios after six years of research and a $1M investment.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Motorola soon began using its trademarked term for the process, PLAcir, in its consumer radio advertisements.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Hallicrafters released its first "foto-etch" printed circuit product, a clock-radio, on November 1, 1952.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Even as circuit boards became available, the point-to-point chassis construction method remained in common use in industry (such as TV and hi-fi sets) into at least the late 1960s.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Printed circuit boards were introduced to reduce the size, weight, and cost of parts of the circuitry.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] In 1960, a small consumer radio receiver might be built with all its circuitry on one circuit board, but a TV set would probably contain one or more circuit boards.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Originally, every electronic component had wire leads, and a PCB had holes drilled for each wire of each component.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] The component leads were then inserted through the holes and soldered to the copper PCB traces.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] This method of assembly is called *through-hole* construction.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Danko of the United States Army Signal Corps developed the *Auto-Sembly* process in which component leads were inserted into a copper foil interconnection pattern and dip soldered.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] The patent they obtained in 1956 was assigned to the U.S.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] With the development of board lamination and etching techniques, this concept evolved into the standard printed circuit board fabrication process in use today.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Soldering could be done automatically by passing the board over a ripple, or wave, of molten solder in a wave-soldering machine.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] However, the wires and holes are inefficient since drilling holes is expensive and consumes drill bits and the protruding wires are cut off and discarded.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Since the 1980s, surface mount parts have increasingly replaced through-hole components, enabling smaller boards and lower production costs, but making repairs more challenging.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] In the 1990s the use of multilayer surface boards became more frequent.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] As a result, size was further minimized and both flexible and rigid PCBs were incorporated in different devices.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] In 1995 PCB manufacturers began using microvia technology to produce High-Density Interconnect (HDI) PCBs.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Recent advances in 3D printing have meant that there are several new techniques in PCB creation.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] 3D printed electronics (PEs) can be utilized to print items layer by layer and subsequently the item can be printed with a liquid ink that contains electronic functionalities.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] HDI (High Density Interconnect) technology allows for a denser design on the PCB and thus potentially smaller PCBs with more traces and components in a given area.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] As a result, the paths between components can be shorter.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] HDIs use blind/buried vias, or a combination that includes microvias.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] With multi-layer HDI PCBs the interconnection of several vias stacked on top of each other (stacked vías, instead of one deep buried via) can be made stronger, thus enhancing reliability in all conditions.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] The most common applications for HDI technology are computer and mobile phone components as well as medical equipment and military communication equipment.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] A 4-layer HDI microvia PCB is equivalent in quality to an 8-layer through-hole PCB, so HDI technology can reduce costs.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] HDI PCBs are often made using build-up film such as ajinomoto build-up film, which is also used in the production of flip chip packages.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Some PCBs have optical waveguides, similar to optical fibers built on the PCB.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] A basic PCB consists of a flat sheet of insulating material and a layer of copper foil, laminated to the substrate.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Chemical etching divides the copper into separate conducting lines called tracks or *circuit traces*, pads for connections, vias to pass connections between layers of copper, and features such as solid conductive areas for electromagnetic shielding or other purposes.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] The tracks function as wires fixed in place, and are insulated from each other by air and the board substrate material.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] The surface of a PCB may have a coating that protects the copper from corrosion and reduces the chances of solder shorts between traces or undesired electrical contact with stray bare wires.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] For its function in helping to prevent solder shorts, the coating is called solder resist or solder mask.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] The pattern to be etched into each copper layer of a PCB is called the "artwork".
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] The etching is usually done using photoresist which is coated onto the PCB, then exposed to light projected in the pattern of the artwork.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] The resist material protects the copper from dissolution into the etching solution.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] A PCB design can be mass-reproduced in a way similar to the way photographs can be mass-duplicated from film negatives using a photographic printer.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] FR-4 glass epoxy is the most common insulating substrate.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Another substrate material is cotton paper impregnated with phenolic resin, often tan or brown.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] A PCB may be printed with a legend identifying the components, test points, or identifying text.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Originally, silkscreen printing was used for this purpose, but today other, finer quality printing methods are usually used.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Normally the legend does not affect the function of a PCBA.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] A printed circuit board can have multiple layers of copper which almost always are arranged in pairs.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] The number of layers and the interconnection designed between them (vias, PTHs) provide a general estimate of the board complexity.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Using more layers allow for more routing options and better control of signal integrity, but are also time-consuming and costly to manufacture.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Likewise, selection of the vias for the board also allow fine tuning of the board size, escaping of signals off complex ICs, routing, and long term reliability, but are tightly coupled with production complexity and cost.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] One of the simplest boards to produce is the two-layer board.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] It has copper on both sides that are referred to as external layers; multi layer boards sandwich additional internal layers of copper and insulation.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] After two-layer PCBs, the next step up is the four-layer.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Only the outer layers need be coated; the inner copper layers are protected by the adjacent substrate layers.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] "Through hole" components are mounted by their wire leads passing through the board and soldered to traces on the other side.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] "Surface mount" components are attached by their leads to copper traces on the same side of the board.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] A board may use both methods for mounting components.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] PCBs with only through-hole mounted components are now uncommon.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Surface mounting is used for transistors, diodes, IC chips, resistors, and capacitors.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Through-hole mounting may be used for some large components such as electrolytic capacitors and connectors.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] The first PCBs used through-hole technology, mounting electronic components by inserting leads through holes on one side of the board and soldering onto copper traces on the other side.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Boards may be single-sided, with an unplated component side, or more compact double-sided boards, with components soldered on both sides.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Leads may be soldered either manually or by a wave soldering machine.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Surface-mount technology emerged in the 1960s, gained momentum in the early 1980s, and became widely used by the mid-1990s.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Components were mechanically redesigned to have small metal tabs or end caps that could be soldered directly onto the PCB surface, instead of wire leads to pass through holes.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Components became much smaller and component placement on both sides of the board became more common than with through-hole mounting, allowing much smaller PCB assemblies with much higher circuit densities.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Surface mounting lends itself well to a high degree of automation, reducing labor costs and greatly increasing production rates compared with through-hole circuit boards.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Components can be supplied mounted on carrier tapes.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Surface mount components can be about one-quarter to one-tenth of the size and weight of through-hole components, and passive components much cheaper.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] However, prices of semiconductor surface mount devices (SMDs) are determined more by the chip itself than the package, with little price advantage over larger packages, and some wire-ended components, such as 1N4148 small-signal switch diodes, are actually significantly cheaper than SMD equivalents.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Each trace consists of a flat, narrow part of the copper foil that remains after etching.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Its resistance, determined by its width, thickness, and length, must be sufficiently low for the current the conductor will carry.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Power and ground traces may need to be wider than signal traces.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] In a multi-layer board one entire layer may be mostly solid copper to act as a ground plane for shielding and power return.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] For microwave circuits and high-speed digital signals (which use similar frequencies), transmission lines can be laid out in a planar form such as stripline or microstrip with carefully controlled dimensions to assure a consistent impedance.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] High density interconnects (HDI) PCBs have tracks or vias with a width or diameter of under 152 micrometers.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Laminates are manufactured by curing layers of cloth or paper with thermoset resin under pressure and heat to form an integral final piece of uniform thickness.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] They can be up to 4 by 8 feet (1.2 by 2.4 m) in width and length.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Varying cloth weaves (threads per inch or cm), cloth thickness, and resin percentage are used to achieve the desired final thickness and dielectric characteristics.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Available standard laminate thickness are listed in ANSI/IPC-D-275.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] The cloth or fiber material used, resin material, and the cloth to resin ratio determine the laminate's type designation (FR-4, CEM-1, G-10, etc.) and therefore the characteristics of the laminate produced.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] There are quite a few different dielectrics that can be chosen to provide different insulating values depending on the requirements of the circuit.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Some of these dielectrics are polytetrafluoroethylene (Teflon), FR-4, FR-1, CEM-1 or CEM-3.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Thermal expansion is an important consideration especially with ball grid array (BGA) and naked die technologies, and glass fiber offers the best dimensional stability.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] FR-4 is by far the most common material used today.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] The board stock with unetched copper on it is called "copper-clad laminate".
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] With decreasing size of board features and increasing frequencies, small non-homogeneities like uneven distribution of fiberglass or other filler, thickness variations, and bubbles in the resin matrix, and the associated local variations in the dielectric constant, are gaining importance.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] The circuit-board substrates are usually dielectric composite materials.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] The composites contain a matrix (usually an epoxy resin) and a reinforcement (usually a woven, sometimes non-woven, glass fibers, sometimes even paper), and in some cases a filler is added to the resin (e.g. ceramics; titanate ceramics can be used to increase the dielectric constant).
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] The reinforcement type defines two major classes of materials: woven and non-woven.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Woven reinforcements are cheaper, but the high dielectric constant of glass may not be favorable for many higher-frequency applications.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] The spatially non-homogeneous structure also introduces local variations in electrical parameters, due to different resin/glass ratio at different areas of the weave pattern.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Non-woven reinforcements, or materials with low or no reinforcement, are more expensive but more suitable for some RF/analog applications.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] At the glass transition temperature the resin in the composite softens and significantly increases thermal expansion; exceeding Tg then exerts mechanical overload on the board components - e.g. the joints and the vias.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Below Tg the thermal expansion of the resin roughly matches copper and glass, above it gets significantly higher.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] As the reinforcement and copper confine the board along the plane, virtually all volume expansion projects to the thickness and stresses the plated-through holes.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Repeated soldering or other exposition to higher temperatures can cause failure of the plating, especially with thicker boards; thick boards therefore require a matrix with a high Tg.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] The materials used determine the substrate's dielectric constant.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] This constant is also dependent on frequency, usually decreasing with frequency.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] As this constant determines the signal propagation speed, frequency dependence introduces phase distortion in wideband applications; as flat a dielectric constant vs frequency characteristics as is achievable is important here.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] The impedance of transmission lines decreases with frequency, therefore faster edges of signals reflect more than slower ones.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Dielectric breakdown voltage determines the maximum voltage gradient the material can be subjected to before suffering a breakdown (conduction, or arcing, through the dielectric).
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Tracking resistance determines how the material resists high voltage electrical discharges creeping over the board surface.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Loss tangent determines how much of the electromagnetic energy from the signals in the conductors is absorbed in the board material.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] This factor is important for high frequencies.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Choosing unnecessarily low-loss material is a common engineering error in high-frequency digital design; it increases the cost of the boards without a corresponding benefit.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Signal degradation by loss tangent and dielectric constant can be easily assessed by an eye pattern.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Moisture absorption occurs when the material is exposed to high humidity or water.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Both the resin and the reinforcement may absorb water; water also may be soaked by capillary forces through voids in the materials and along the reinforcement.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Epoxies of the FR-4 materials are not too susceptible, with absorption of only 0.15%.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Teflon has very low absorption of 0.01%.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Polyimides and cyanate esters, on the other side, suffer from high water absorption.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Absorbed water can lead to significant degradation of key parameters; it impairs tracking resistance, breakdown voltage, and dielectric parameters.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Relative dielectric constant of water is about 73, compared to about 4 for common circuit board materials.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Absorbed moisture can also vaporize on heating, as during soldering, and cause cracking and delamination, the same effect responsible for "popcorning" damage on wet packaging of electronic parts.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Careful baking of the substrates may be required to dry them prior to soldering.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Copper thickness of PCBs can be specified directly or as the weight of copper per area (in ounce per square foot) which is easier to measure.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] One ounce per square foot is 34 μm (0.0013 in) thickness.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] *Heavy copper* is a layer exceeding three ounces of copper per ft2, or approximately 105 μm (0.0041 in) thick.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Heavy copper layers are used for high current or to help dissipate heat.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] On the common FR-4 substrates, 1 oz copper per ft2 (35 μm (0.0014 in)) is the most common thickness; 2 oz (70 μm (0.0028 in)) and 0.5 oz (17.5 μm (0.00069 in)) thickness is often an option.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Flexible substrates typically have thinner metalization.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Metal-core boards for high power devices commonly use thicker copper; 35 μm (0.0014 in) is usual but also 140 μm (0.0055 in) and 400 μm (0.016 in) can be encountered.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] In the US, copper foil thickness is specified in units of ounces per square foot (oz/ft2), commonly referred to simply as *ounce*.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] 1/2 oz/ft2 foil is not widely used as a finished copper weight, but is used for outer layers when plating for through holes will increase the finished copper weight.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Some PCB manufacturers refer to 1 oz/ft2 copper foil as having a thickness of 35 μm (0.0014 in) (may also be referred to as 35 μ, 35 micron, or 35 mic).
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Printed circuit board manufacturing involves manufacturing bare printed circuit boards and then populating them with electronic components.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] In large-scale board manufacturing, multiple PCBs are grouped on a single panel for efficient processing.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] After assembly, they are separated (depaneled).
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] A minimal PCB for a single component, used for prototyping, is called a **breakout board**.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] The purpose of a breakout board is to "break out" the leads of a component on separate terminals so that manual connections to them can be made easily.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Breakout boards are especially used for surface-mount components or any components with fine lead pitch.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Advanced PCBs may contain components embedded in the substrate, such as capacitors and integrated circuits, to reduce the amount of space taken up by components on the surface of the PCB while improving electrical characteristics.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Multiwire is a patented technique of interconnection which uses machine-routed insulated wires embedded in a non-conducting matrix (often plastic resin).
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] As of 2010, Multiwire is still available through Hitachi.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Corrections can be made to a Multiwire board layout more easily than to a PCB layout.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Before the advent of integrated circuits, *cordwood construction* allowed the highest possible component packing density.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] The construction method was used with wire-ended components in applications where space was at a premium (such as fuzes, missile guidance, and telemetry systems) and in the high-speed computers of the day, where short traces were important.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] In cordwood construction, axial-leaded components were mounted between two parallel planes.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] The name comes from the way axial-lead components (capacitors, resistors, coils, and diodes) are stacked in parallel rows and columns, like a stack of firewood.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] The components were either soldered together with jumper wire or they were connected to other components by thin nickel ribbon welded at right angles onto the component leads.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Some versions of cordwood construction used soldered single-sided PCBs as the interconnection method (as pictured), allowing the use of normal-leaded components at the cost of being difficult to remove the boards or replace any component that is not at the edge.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Cordwood construction was replaced with multi-layer board, SMD and ICs.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] A **Flexible Printed Circuit Board (FPCB)** is a thin, lightweight circuit made from flexible materials like polyimide.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] It can bend or fold while maintaining reliable electrical connections and is commonly used in compact electronic devices such as smartphones, wearables, and medical equipment.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Printed circuit boards have been used as an alternative to their typical use for electronic and biomedical engineering thanks to the versatility of their layers, especially the copper layer.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Manufacturers may not support component-level repair of printed circuit boards because of the relatively low cost to replace compared with the time and cost of troubleshooting to a component level.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] In board-level repair, the technician identifies the board (PCA) on which the fault resides and replaces it.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] In many countries (including all European Single Market participants, the United Kingdom, Turkey, and China), legislation restricts the use of lead, cadmium, and mercury in electrical equipment.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] PCBs sold in such countries must therefore use lead-free manufacturing processes and lead-free solder, and attached components must themselves be compliant.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Safety Standard UL 796 covers component safety requirements for printed wiring boards for use as components in devices or appliances.
[src:altium-designer/printed-circuit-board] Testing analyzes characteristics such as flammability, maximum operating temperature, electrical tracking, heat deflection, and direct support of live electrical parts.
[src:altium-designer/schematic-capture] The circuit design is the first step of actual design of an electronic circuit.
[src:altium-designer/schematic-capture] Typically sketches are drawn on paper, and then entered into a computer using a schematic editor.
[src:altium-designer/schematic-capture] Therefore schematic entry is said to be a front-end operation of several others in the design flow.
[src:altium-designer/schematic-capture] Despite the complexity of modern components – huge ball grid arrays and tiny passive components – schematic capture is easier today than it has been for many years.
[src:altium-designer/schematic-capture] CAD software is easier to use and is available in full-featured expensive packages, very capable mid-range packages that sometimes have free versions and completely free versions that are either open source or directly linked to a printed circuit board fabrication company.
[src:altium-designer/schematic-capture] In past years, schematic diagrams with mostly discrete components were fairly readable.
[src:altium-designer/schematic-capture] However, with the newer high pin-count parts and with the almost universal use of standard letter- or A4-sized paper, schematics have become less so.
[src:altium-designer/schematic-capture] Many times, there will be a single large part on a page with nothing but pin reference keys to connect it to other pages.
[src:altium-designer/schematic-capture] Readability levels can be enhanced by using buses and superbuses, related pins can be connected into a common bus and routed to other pages.
[src:altium-designer/schematic-capture] Buses don't need to be just the traditional address or data bus directly linked pins.
[src:altium-designer/schematic-capture] A bus grouping can also be used for related uses, such as all analog input or all communications related pin functions.
[src:altium-designer/schematic-capture] After the circuit design is captured in a schematic, most EDA tools allow the design to be simulated.
[src:altium-designer/schematic-capture] Schematic capture involves not only entering the circuits into the CAD system, but also generally calls for decisions that may seem more appropriate for later in the design, such as package choice.
[src:altium-designer/schematic-capture] Although you may be able to change the package later, many PCB CAD systems ask you to choose both the part and package when placing it into the schematic capture program.
[src:altium-designer/schematic-capture] This also brings into play such considerations as prototyping and assembly.
[src:altium-designer/schematic-capture] In a high-volume assembly environment, there will be plenty of opportunities for DFM analysis.
[src:altium-designer/schematic-capture] However, in a rapid prototyping environment such as at assembly houses specializing in low-volume/high-mix and quick turnaround times, the pick and place machines are programmed directly from the board layout files.
[src:altium-designer/schematic-capture] Careful package selection during schematic capture will save time during the assembly and debug process.
[src:altium-designer/schematic-capture] With new parts, the CAD system may not have your chosen component in its parts library, so you may need to create the parts library yourself.
[src:altium-designer/schematic-capture] Again, you may at the time not be overly concerned with the package, but careful creation of the part library will save time and risk later.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] An SMT component is usually smaller than its through-hole counterpart because it has either smaller leads or no leads at all.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] It may have short pins or leads of various styles, flat contacts, a matrix of solder balls (BGAs), or terminations on the body of the component.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Surface-mount technology was developed in the 1960s.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] By 1986, surface-mounted components accounted for 10% of the market at most but were rapidly gaining popularity.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] By the late 1990s, the great majority of high-tech electronic printed circuit assemblies were dominated by surface mount devices.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Much of the pioneering work in this technology was done by IBM.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] The design approach first demonstrated by IBM in 1960 in a small-scale computer was later applied in the Launch Vehicle Digital Computer used in the Instrument Unit that guided all Saturn IB and Saturn V vehicles.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Components were mechanically redesigned to have small metal tabs or end caps that could be directly soldered to the surface of the PCB.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Components became much smaller, and component placement on both sides of a board became far more common with surface mounting than through-hole mounting, allowing much higher circuit densities and smaller circuit boards and, in turn, machines or subassemblies containing the boards.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Often, the surface tension of the solder is enough to hold the parts to the board; in rare cases, parts on the bottom or "second" side of the board may be secured with adhesive to keep components from dropping off inside reflow ovens.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Adhesive is sometimes used to hold SMT components on the bottom side of a board if a wave soldering process is used to solder both SMT and through-hole components simultaneously.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Surface mounting lends itself well to a high degree of automation, reducing labor cost and greatly increasing production rates.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Conversely, SMT does not lend itself well to manual or low-automation fabrication, which is more economical and faster for one-off prototyping and small-scale production; this is one reason why many through-hole components are still manufactured.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Some SMDs can be soldered with a temperature-controlled manual soldering iron, but those that are very small or have too fine a lead pitch are often almost impossible to manually solder without expensive equipment.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Different terms describe the components, technique, and machines used in manufacturing.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Where components are to be placed, the printed circuit board normally has flat, usually tin-lead, silver, or gold plated copper pads without holes, called *solder pads*.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Solder paste, a sticky mixture of flux and tiny solder particles, is first applied to all the solder pads with a stainless steel or nickel stencil using a screen printing process.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] It can also be applied by a jet-printing mechanism, similar to an inkjet printer.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] After pasting, the boards proceed to the pick-and-place machines, where they are placed on a conveyor belt.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] The components to be placed on the boards are usually delivered to the production line in either paper/plastic tapes wound on reels or plastic tubes.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Some large integrated circuits are delivered in static-free trays.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Numerical control pick-and-place machines remove the parts from the tapes, tubes or trays and place them on the PCB.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] The boards are then conveyed into the reflow soldering oven.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] They first enter a pre-heat zone, where the temperature of the board and all the components is gradually, uniformly raised to prevent thermal shock.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] The boards then enter a zone where the temperature is high enough to melt the solder particles in the solder paste, bonding the component leads to the pads on the circuit board.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] The surface tension of the molten solder helps keep the components in place.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] If the solder pad geometries are correctly designed, surface tension automatically aligns the components on their pads.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] There are a number of *techniques* for reflowing solder.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] One is to use infrared lamps; this is called infrared reflow.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Another technology that is becoming popular again is special fluorocarbon liquids with high boiling points which use a method called vapor phase reflow.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Due to environmental concerns, this method was falling out of favor until lead-free legislation was introduced which requires tighter controls on soldering.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] At the end of 2008, convection soldering was the most popular reflow technology using either standard air or nitrogen gas.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Each method has its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] With infrared reflow, the board designer must lay the board out so that short components do not fall into the shadows of tall components.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Component location is less restricted if the designer knows that vapor phase reflow or convection soldering will be used in production.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Following reflow soldering, certain irregular or heat-sensitive components may be installed and soldered by hand, or in large-scale automation, by focused infrared beam (FIB) or localized convection equipment.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] If the circuit board is double-sided then this printing, placement, reflow process may be repeated using either solder paste or glue to hold the components in place.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] If a wave soldering process is used, then the parts must be glued to the board before processing to prevent them from floating off when the solder paste holding them in place is melted.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] After soldering, the boards may be washed to remove flux residues and any stray solder balls that could short out closely spaced component leads.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Rosin flux is removed with fluorocarbon solvents, high flash point hydrocarbon solvents, or low flash solvents e.g. limonene (derived from orange peels) which require extra rinsing or drying cycles.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Water-soluble fluxes are removed with deionized water and detergent, followed by an air blast to quickly remove residual water.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] However, most electronic assemblies are made using a "No-Clean" process where the flux residues are designed to be left on the circuit board, since they are considered harmless.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] This saves the cost of cleaning, speeds up the manufacturing process, and reduces waste.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] However, it is generally suggested to wash the assembly, even when a "No-Clean" process is used, when the application uses very high frequency clock signals (in excess of 1 GHz).
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Another reason to remove no-clean residues is to improve adhesion of conformal coatings and underfill materials.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Certain manufacturing standards, such as those written by the IPC – Association Connecting Electronics Industries require cleaning regardless of the solder flux type used to ensure a thoroughly clean board.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Proper cleaning removes all traces of solder flux, as well as dirt and other contaminants that may be invisible to the naked eye.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] No-Clean or other soldering processes may leave "white residues" that, according to IPC, are acceptable "provided that these residues have been qualified and documented as benign".
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] However, while shops conforming to IPC standards are expected to adhere to the Association's rules on board condition, not all manufacturing facilities apply IPC standards, nor are they required to do so.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Additionally, in some applications, such as low-end electronics, such stringent manufacturing methods are excessive both in expense and time required.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Finally, the boards are visually inspected for missing or misaligned components and solder bridging.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] If needed, they are sent to a rework station where a human operator repairs any errors.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] They are then usually sent to the testing stations (in-circuit testing and/or functional testing) to verify that they operate correctly.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Automated optical inspection (AOI) systems are commonly used in PCB manufacturing.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] This technology has proven highly efficient for process improvements and quality achievements.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Defective surface-mount components can be repaired by using soldering irons (for some connections) or a non-contact rework system.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] In most cases, a rework system is the better choice because SMD work with a soldering iron requires considerable skill and is not always feasible.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Sometimes hundreds or thousands of the same part need to be repaired.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] If due to assembly, such errors are often caught during the process.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] However, a whole new level of rework arises when component failure is discovered too late, and perhaps unnoticed until the end user of the device being manufactured experiences it.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Rework can also be used if products of sufficient value to justify it require revision or re-engineering, perhaps to change a single firmware-based component.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Reworking in large volumes requires an operation designed for that purpose.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] There are essentially two non-contact soldering/desoldering methods: infrared soldering and soldering with hot gas.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] With infrared soldering, the energy for heating up the solder joint is transmitted by long-, medium- or short-wave infrared electromagnetic radiation.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] During hot gas soldering, the energy for heating up the solder joint is transmitted by a hot gas.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] This can be air or inert gas (nitrogen).
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Surface-mount components are usually smaller than their counterparts with leads, and are designed to be handled by machines rather than by humans.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] The electronics industry has standardized package shapes and sizes (the leading standardisation body is JEDEC).
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] For 5% precision SMD resistors usually are marked with their resistance values using three digits: two significant digits and a multiplier digit.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] These are quite often white lettering on a black background, but other colored backgrounds and lettering can be used.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] For 1% precision SMD resistors, the code is used, as three digits would otherwise not convey enough information.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] of values, while the letter indicates the multiplier.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Non-electrolytic capacitors are usually unmarked and the only reliable method of determining their value is removal from the circuit and subsequent measurement with a capacitance meter or impedance bridge.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] The materials used to fabricate the capacitors, such as nickel tantalate, possess different colours and these can give an approximate idea of the capacitance of the component.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Generally physical size is proportional to capacitance and voltage for the same dielectric.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] For example, a 100 nF, 50 V capacitor may come in the same package as a 10 nF, 150 V device.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] SMD (non-electrolytic) capacitors, which are usually monolithic ceramic capacitors, exhibit the same body color on all four faces not covered by the end caps.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Smaller inductance with moderately high current ratings are usually of the ferrite bead type.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] They are simply a metal conductor looped through a ferrite bead and almost the same as their through-hole versions but possess SMD end caps rather than leads.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] They appear dark grey and are magnetic, unlike capacitors with a similar dark grey appearance.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] (nH) range and are often used as power supply rail decouplers or in high frequency parts of a circuit.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Larger inductors and transformers may of course be through-hole mounted on the same board.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] SMT inductors with larger inductance values often have turns of wire or flat strap around the body or embedded in clear epoxy, allowing the wire or strap to be seen.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] These higher inductance types are often limited to small current ratings, although some of the flat strap types can handle a few amps.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] As with capacitors, component values and identifiers for smaller inductors are not usually marked on the component itself; if not documented or printed on the PCB, measurement, usually removed from the circuit, is the only way of determining them.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Larger inductors, especially wire-wound types in larger footprints, usually have the value printed on the top.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Discrete semiconductors, such as diodes and transistors are often marked with a two- or three-symbol code.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] The same code marked on different packages or on devices from different manufacturers can translate to different devices.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] Many of these codes, used because the devices are too small to be marked with more traditional numbers used on larger packages, correlate to more familiar traditional part numbers when a correlation list is consulted.
[src:altium-designer/surface-mount-technology] is also available, although these lists are not complete.
